{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"9b1becae-1596-41de-8f2e-115ce89ccd93","content":"The repository is empty, so there's no project-specific documentation to reference. Here's the general guidance based on .NET and macOS knowledge:\n\n### Recovering a crash dump on macOS without `createdump`\n\n1. **Enable macOS core dumps:**\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n\n2. **Set the core dump directory** (macOS stores them in `/cores/` by default):\n   ```bash\n   ls /cores/\n   ```\n\n3. **Reproduce the crash** — run your NativeAOT app. macOS should write a core file like `/cores/core.<pid>`.\n\n4. **If `/cores/` is empty**, ensure SIP isn't blocking core dumps:\n   ```bash\n   sudo sysctl kern.coredump=1\n   ```\n\n5. **Analyze with `lldb`** (since NativeAOT produces native binaries, `lldb` works directly):\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /cores/core.<pid> ./your-app\n   ```\n   Then use `bt` for a backtrace, `frame variable` to inspect locals, etc.\n\n6. **Alternative — use macOS Crash Reports:** Check `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` for `.ips` or `.crash` files generated automatically by ReportCrash.\n\n**Key point:** Since NativeAOT apps are fully native, you don't need `createdump` (which is a .NET runtime tool). Standard OS-level core dump and `lldb` workflows apply directly.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c28c3abe-cb41-44bf-b997-9c790e88d84b","outputTokens":360,"requestId":"D80A:1E89:1BD02C8:1F0B25B:69FBF092"},"id":"6ebc39f0-30c6-4f7a-ac0c-bdc2a866bc6e","timestamp":"2026-05-07T01:53:32.869Z","parentId":"1159dc5b-ec5c-4e47-b764-76ff8972115d"}
